            <h1>Fundamental Rights in the Indian Constitution</h1>
            <p>Fundamental Rights are essential freedoms granted to all citizens, ensuring equality, dignity, and freedom in the democratic framework of India.</p>
        </header>

        <section>
            <h2>Overview of Fundamental Rights</h2>
            <p>Enshrined in Part III of the Indian Constitution, Fundamental Rights provide citizens with essential protections and freedoms. These rights are considered the bedrock of democracy and cover various aspects of personal and social life.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Types of Fundamental Rights</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <h3>Right to Equality</h3>
                    <p>Prohibits discrimination on grounds of religion, race, caste, sex, or place of birth. It also ensures equality before the law and equal protection of the laws.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Right to Freedom</h3>
                    <p>Includes freedom of speech and expression, assembly, association, movement, residence, and profession.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Right Against Exploitation</h3>
                    <p>Prohibits human trafficking, forced labor, and employment of children in hazardous conditions.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Right to Freedom of Religion</h3>
                    <p>Ensures freedom of conscience and free profession, practice, and propagation of religion.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Cultural and Educational Rights</h3>
                    <p>Protects the rights of cultural, linguistic minorities by enabling them to preserve their heritage and establishes the right to education.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Right to Constitutional Remedies</h3>
                    <p>Empowers citizens to approach the courts if any of their Fundamental Rights are violated, known as the "heart and soul" of the Constitution by Dr. B.R. Ambedkar.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Importance of Fundamental Rights</h2>
            <p>Fundamental Rights safeguard individual liberties and maintain a just and equitable society. They empower citizens, promote social harmony, and are vital to sustaining democracy in India.</p>
